6.","meanings":["French: variant of   Bonneville   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."],"variants":[{"name":"Bonneville","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Francois, Liette, Normand, Pierre.","French: habitational name from any of numerous places called Bonneville, from Old French <i>bonne</i> ‘good’ + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. Compare   Bonville  .","Altered form of French <b>Bonnevialle</b>: habitational name from Bonnevialle in the central part of France."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":29,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William Bonville was born about 1230, in Devon, England, his father, Nicholas Bonville, was 19 and his mother, Amesia Of Wiscomb, was 16. He married Joan Ferrers about 1259, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1268, in his hometown,